fields.BIO:
Janet currently serves as the Clean Energy Program Coordinator for the City of Savannah Office of Sustainability. She is responsible for supporting the implementation of the 100% Savannah Plan which pledges to meet 100% of community-wide electricity needs with clean and renewable energy by 2035. A central focus of her efforts revolves around discovering creative approaches to leverage the clean energy transition in order to redress past injustices and create opportunities for frontline, fence-line, and low-income communities.  

Janet recently graduated from the University of Georgia with a Bachelor‚Äôs degree in Environmental Health Science. While a student, she worked as a Climate and Health intern for the New Orleans Health Department. She focused on how minorities who live near industry-caused pollution are disproportionately affected by climate change and used the only Superfund site in New Orleans as her case study. She is very passionate about environmental public health, environmental justice, and renewable energy. When she‚Äôs not working, Janet enjoys sleeping, eating, watching football (GO DAWGS!!!), traveling, hiking, and binge-watching television.

fields.BIO:
Bringing in over two years of previous experience, Alexis Blomqvist joined the EVNoire team in March of 2021 and currently serves as the manager of Data and Research for the organization. In her capacity, she has overseen the management and implementation of research in 16 states across the United States across a variety of topics such as resource allocation in charging station deployment, electric vehicle accessibility and affordability, and transportation burden and barriers faced in frontline communities all across the country. In her tenure, she has provided critical oversight for research efforts that have garnered over 22,000 responses from respondents in critical communities such as Black, Latine and Tribal communities, as well as low-income, rural, and under-resourced communities. Alexis‚Äô work has been featured in projects on behalf of partners such as Uber, Ford, and the Department of Energy, and has played a role in shaping developments in city governments and utilities across the country. 

Alexis Blomqvist graduated magna cum laude from Ohio State University in 2020 with a degree in Foreign Policy and Security, alongside two minors in Spanish and International Development. She has working fluency in Spanish and Swedish, and has proficiency in programs such as R, Tableau, and Qualtrics, as well as mapping software such as Datawrapper. Her expertise merges a robust understanding of demographic data and its applications with research design, paving the way for critical insights into the connections between quantifiable measures and communities‚Äô lived experiences.

fields.BIO:
I am Jawno, a creative organizer and gardener dedicated to cultivating just, regenerative futures through accessible cultural experiences, inspiring creative works, and good trouble. In my philanthropic work, I strive to connect Black, Indigenous, and other Global Majority communities with the tools and resources necessary to realize resource sovereignty and climate resilience.

As a descendant of Indigenous African stewards in Nigeria and Southern Black farmers in the Southeast U.S., I have witnessed firsthand the impacts of environmental degradation and industrial agriculture, which have displaced my family from the land they have harmonized with for generations. My pre-med studies at Stanford University deepened my understanding of how environmental harm exacerbates climate catastrophes and adversely affects the health and livelihoods of marginalized communities.

After graduating from Stanford in 2021, I focused on climate change and environmental justice, particularly in the realms of permaculture, agroecology, and traditional Indigenous agricultural practices. My work aims to explore and promote these interconnected practices as powerful alternatives to the dominant modes of land and resource extraction that jeopardize our planet today.

Currently, as a Program Associate at the Waverley Street Foundation, I collaborate with our team and external partners to design and deliver grants focused on natural farming, renewable energy, and joy. I have also contributed significantly to shaping foundation strategies, especially around global youth activism and land-based liberation.

I started Get Free Food to inspire and empower communities to reclaim their food sovereignty through joyous, culturally resonant gatherings. By collaborating with local farmers, chefs, artists, community orgs, and educators, we ensure that everyone has access to healthy, free food while fostering a sense of belonging and regeneration. We envision a food movement where everyone can find belonging ‚Äî place by place, moment by moment, meal by meal. We must make the good food revolution irresistible.

My passion for Black and Indigenous liberation, climate justice, and youth education is complemented by my interests in poetry, food and land sovereignty, revolutionary aesthetics, and Afrofuturism. I continue to engage in intergenerational, intersectional, and international efforts to build just resource systems, reinvigorate sovereignty, and create sanctuaries for marginalized communities.

fields.BIO:
Julian Gordon received a M.S. in Physics, Fall 2019, from North Carolina A&T State University majoring in Atmospheric Science & Meteorology. He's been playing drums all his life, in concert band, jazz band, marching band -snare, downright tenor, and bass w/ CREAM drumline and North Carolina A&T, Section Leader @ North Atlanta High 2010-2012, APS Youth Orchestra, Drumline LIVE, and multiple genres with bands playing drumset, hand drums, and many auxiliary percussion instruments. He received instruction in African drumming with the dancers of E. Gwynn Dance Troupe, as well as Zodwa Dance Company in North Carolina. He also produces music on Logic Pro X if anyone is interested in audio production.
 He also works heavily as an environmental justice activist, constructing videos with SolNation.org. His love for the atmosphere above us has transferred to becoming an FAA-Certified Remote Pilot and Commisioner of the Environmental Justice and Technologies Commision with SkylineVideoPros.com, as well as consulting with many businesses and organizations. He is excited to combine his expertise as the Atlanta Branch Leader as well as Drums and Drones professor with the Black Achievement Fund.

fields.BIO:
Named one of 100 young Mandelas of the future by News24, Masabata Sebusi is a 27 year from the Free
State who is passionate about building sustainable communities and changing lives. She is an entrepreneur,
speaker and a leader.

She holds a Bcom Accounting degree and a Postgraduate Diploma in Financial Planning Law both from the
University of the Free State. Her love for entrepreneurship was sparked when she joined Enactus in
University. This was where she co-founded her first enterprise and learned valuable lessons that have
helped her mature as a leader.

She runs an agribusiness that facilitates access to market for small holder farmers from marginalized
communities. The company has made huge strides within just a few months of launching. It launched a
female farmer accelerator programme that empowered 50 female farmers with skills and insights that will
enable them to grow and scale their business.

For her, being a change agent believes using the skills she has gained to improve the lives of those around
her.She is the African ambassador for World Business Dialogue and the Womenboss society. Masabata
has received national and international recognition from News24, UFS Built, Mail&Guardian, BrandAfrica,
Business day TV, Women of Wonder and her latest recognition SheAwards Agripreneur of the year under
30 in 2023.

She believes that young people play a critical role in building our society and is committed to improving
lives and creating real impact through the work she does. This is lastly demonstrated through the work she
does at AgriVuno through incubating farmer enterprises.

Abubakr Muhammad Karim specializes in developing organizational and operational services to non-profit groups and providing business management consulting to profit making entities. Karim engages in projects involving land management, international research, health & healing, life skills training, academic instructions, and social service delivery.  He is an avid gardener and writer of subjects on food science, community sustainability and spiritual awareness. 

Karim has spent most of his life assisting organizations in developing the capacity to improve their state of operations and strategic planning processes. His latest vision is to establish a ‚ÄúNature Culture‚Äù philosophy and project combining multiple holistic activities, disciplines, and environments where brain function is enhanced, body cells are renewed, and individuals achieve greater awareness of ‚Äúself‚Äù. He presently spends a great deal of focus researching the propagation of plants for medicinal and culinary uses.
Karim holds a master‚Äôs degree in Community Economic Development and lives in Tuskegee Alabama where the population is 98% black.
